      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm studying for my meteorology exam and I'm a bit stuck on Clear Air Turbulence (CAT). Can you explain the physical causes behind it, especially how the jet stream plays a role? Also, why is it so hard for standard onboard weather radar to pick it up compared to convective turbulence? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Clear Air Turbulence (CAT) is a fascinating topic, and I'd be happy to help you understand it. CAT is essentially turbulence that occurs in the absence of any visible clouds or precipitation, which is why it's a challenge to detect using standard weather radar. The physical causes behind CAT are quite interesting, and they're closely tied to the jet stream, which is a high-altitude wind current that can create areas of turbulence by disrupting the airflow around mountains or other obstacles.\n\nImagine a group of rowdy, mischievous children (like a group of energetic, mischievous, and unpredictable little goblins) playing in a crowded hallway, causing the floor to vibrate and making it difficult to walk. This is roughly the effect that the jet stream has on the atmosphere, creating areas of turbulence that can be felt by aircraft even when there are no clouds or precipitation in sight.\n\nThe jet stream acts as a kind of \"turbulence generator\" by creating areas of wind shear, which is a change in wind speed or direction with height. This shear can cause air to be forced upwards, creating areas of instability that can lead to turbulence. When an aircraft flies through one of these areas, it can experience significant turbulence, even if",
      "source": "target",
